      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "bfe08879_a99249f3",
      "file_path": "docs/Chapter8/VES_Registraion_3_2.rst",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 201,
      "message": "The latest YAML version is 1.2, however statement about '...' indicating end of document without automatically starting new one is still valid. But meaning is a bit different, e g you can have multiple end markers following each other before the next document. See e g section 9.2 in YAML 1.2 about 'intentionally sloppy format'. At the same time it seems you don't need to include '---' before document if you have an end marker and don't use any '%' directives before next document.\nI guess general question is if there is reason to propose a more restrictive syntax here, because we think some parsers don't correctly support the full YAML 1.2 syntax correctly?",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5279,
        "name": "Oskar Malm",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "oskar.malm@ericsson.com",
        "username": "eoskmal"
      },
      "updated": "2020-03-03 14:03:42.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "c74592ed_db3d21c0",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "8bf0ca6b_f5a2642e",
      "file_path": "docs/Chapter8/VES_Registraion_3_2.rst",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 193,
      "message": "Per https://yaml.org/spec/1.2/spec.html section 2.2 - the ... denotes the end of a document - not just a file.  That's the language pulled from the spec with an associated example",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 3999,
        "name": "Trevor Lovett",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "trevor.lovett@att.com",
        "username": "tl2972"
      },
      "updated": "2020-03-04 02:29:16.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "c04c34f0_624fb583",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "073c87fb_2119d2e4",
      "file_path": "docs/Chapter8/VES_Registraion_3_2.rst",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 201,
      "message": "I tested this with several validators and parsers locally, and didn't run into any issues with how this is specifies.  With no evidence to denote the current examples and wording cause a problem, I'd like to just leave this as is for now.  We've stated that the ... is not required.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 3999,
        "name": "Trevor Lovett",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "trevor.lovett@att.com",
        "username": "tl2972"
      },
      "updated": "2020-03-04 02:29:16.000000000",
